                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/9943: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bulgaria</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Earle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sofia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-13T23:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 13, 1941—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 14—8:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>185. Department’s 35, April 1 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>].<note n="70"
                        xml:id="d322fn70">See footnote 68, <ref target="#pg_300">p.
                        300</ref>.</note> Have emphasized to the Foreign Minister again and again
                    and recently America’s determination that Great Britain and her allies must win
                    this war and that the mighty resources of our country would be used to the limit
                    for this purpose. Also that an act of aggression by Bulgaria against her invaded
                    neighbors would make a terrible impression upon our people and our
                    Government.</p>
                <p>Will see Foreign Minister as soon as possible and reiterate the substance of No.
                    35.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Earle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
